                    class="img-responsive owl-first-image owl-lazy default"
                    width="1763"
                    height="1175"
                    data-src="https://bloximages.newyork1.vip.townnews.com/richmond.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/2/1b/21bc8b1a-1da2-57cc-8cac-3662936a2bca/66217143c8722.image.jpg?resize=750%2C500" />
            </div>
                                        
                                        </a><div class="clearfix"></div>
                                </div>
        <div class="caption-container">
            <div class="caption-inner-c775e442-fe75-11ee-8883-a714ad200d06 collapse in"><div class="caption-text"><p>Richmond Police Chief Rick Edwards gives the quarterly crime briefing at headquarters on Thursday. Edwards began the briefing by discussing a streak of killings from the past three weeks, which cast a pall over a presentation that might have otherwise been lightened by good news.</p></div><div class="card-meta">
                        <ul class="list-inline">
                                    
                                    
